#Text=Lady of the Dunes
#Text=Not to be confused with The Woman in the Dunes .
#Text=Lady of the Dunes ( also known as Lady in the Dunes ) is the nickname for an unidentified woman discovered on July 26 , 1974 in the Race Point Dunes , Provincetown , Massachusetts . [ 2 ] [ 3 ]
#Text=Her body was exhumed in 1980 , 2000 , and 2013 [ 4 ] in efforts to identify her and her murderer ; to date , these efforts have been unsuccessful . [ 5 ] [ 6 ] [ 7 ]
#Text=The case was featured on the television series Haunting Evidence in 2006 . [ 8 ]
#Text=Discovery
#Text=The body of the victim upon her discovery
#Text=A teenage girl found the woman 's body July 26 , 1974 . [ 9 ] [ 10 ] [ 11 ]
#Text=The remains were just yards away from a road , and had a significant amount of insect activity . [ 9 ]
#Text=Two sets of footprints led to the body , and tire tracks were found 50 yards ( 46m ) from the scene . [ 11 ]
#Text=The woman may have died two weeks before her body was found . [ 12 ]
#Text=The victim was face-down on half of a beach blanket .
#Text=There was no sign of a struggle ; police theorized she either knew her killer or had been asleep when she died .
#Text=A blue bandanna and pair of Wrangler jeans were under her head . [ 13 ] [ 3 ] [ 14 ] [ 15 ]
#Text=She had long auburn or red hair , pulled back into a ponytail with a gold-flecked elastic band .
#Text=Her toenails were painted pink .

#Text=Police determined the woman was approximately 5feet 6inches ( 168cm ) tall ( initially believed to have been 5'8 " [ 16 ] ) , weighed 145 pounds ( 66kg ) , and had an athletic build . [ 17 ] [ 18 ]
#Text=Several of her teeth had been removed . [ 13 ] [ 3 ] [ 16 ] [ 19 ]
#Text=One hand and one forearm were missing .
#Text=Most sources say she was between 25 and 40 years old .
#Text=However , she could have been as young as 20 or as old as 49 . [ 20 ] [ 10 ] [ 21 ]
#Text=The woman was nearly decapitated , possibly from strangulation ; one side of her head had been crushed with ( possibly ) a military-entrenching type of tool .
#Text=This head injury was what killed her . [ 13 ] [ 19 ] [ 22 ]
#Text=There were also signs of sexual assault , likely postmortem . [ 13 ] [ 7 ] [ 16 ]
#Text=Some investigators feel the missing teeth , hands , and forearm indicate the killer wanted to hide either the victim 's identity or their own . [ 23 ]
#Text=The woman was buried in October 1974 after the case went cold . [ 11 ]
#Text=In 2014 , one of the case investigators raised funds for a new casket , because the original thin metal casket was rusted and deteriorated . [ 9 ] [ 21 ]
#Text=Investigation
#Text=Other depictions of the victim , created between 1979 and 2006
#Text=Police pored through thousands of missing-person cases and a list of approved vehicles driven through the area ; no matches were found .
#Text=At the scene , the sand and beach blanket were not disturbed . [ 13 ]
#Text=No other evidence was found ( besides the jeans , bandanna , blanket and ponytail holder ) despite extensive searches of the surrounding dunes . [ 11 ]
#Text=The first facial reconstruction of the woman was created with clay in 1979 . [ 16 ]
#Text=Her remains were exhumed in 1980 for examination ; no new clues were uncovered ( although the skull was not buried at the time ) . [ 16 ]
#Text=The body was exhumed again in March 2000 for DNA . [ 23 ] [ 24 ]
#Text=In May 2010 , her skull was placed through a CT scanner that generated images that were then used by the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children for another reconstruction . [ 25 ]
#Text=Leads
#Text=In 1987 , a Canadian woman told a friend that she saw her father strangle a woman in Massachusetts around 1972 .
#Text=Police attempted to locate the woman but were unsuccessful .
#Text=Another woman told police the reconstruction of the victim looked like her sister , who disappeared in Boston in 1974 . [ 16 ]
#Text=Investigators also followed a lead involving Rory Gene Kesinger , who would have been 25 years old at the time of the murder ( she broke out of jail in 1973 ) .
#Text=Authorities saw a resemblance between Kesinger and the victim . [ 23 ]
#Text=However , DNA from Kesinger 's mother did not match the victim . [ 2 ] [ 15 ] [ 26 ]
#Text=Two other missing women , Francis Ewalt of Montana and Vicke Lamberton of Massachusetts have also been ruled out . [ 10 ]
#Text=Jaws film extra possibility
#Text=In August 2015 , speculation arose that Lady of the Dunes may have been an extra in the 1975 film Jaws ( filmed in Massachusetts in 1974 ) .
#Text=Joe Hill , the son of horror author Stephen King , brought this to police attention .
#Text=Hill had learned of the case after reading The Skeleton Crew : How Amateur Sleuths are Solving America 's Coldest Cases just weeks before .
#Text=Hill told an FBI investigator that during the film 's " July 4th Crowd Arrives " sequence , he saw a woman resembling reconstructions of the victim .

#Text=Jaws was shot between May and October 1974 .
